Robert B. McGehee (rbm@faser.cs.olemiss.edu) wrote:

: 4 years ago when i got my first 486-33, this is what the motherboard was 
: like.
: It was a Micronics full size board, 8 ISA slots, and 16 SIMM slots (4 
: banks of 4).  
: Why is it today that all we get is baby-AT motherboards, that have the 
: PCI or ISA slots blocked by the CPU (heat sink), and only 4 SIMM slots.  
: Most power users have tower cases, why not make full size boards?
: Well that is what I want to know.  Do any full size Pentium boards exist 
: today?  If so, who makes them with what chipset?  I heard that 
: multi-processor boards were full size, maybe I should go that route, if 
: it is the only way!  thanks for any advice.

--

I used to work for a really big mom board company. People wanted smaller cases
so they wanted baby-AT boards. We were pretty careful to keep as many of the
slots as possible able to accomadate full length ISA cards.

These days, there are very few full length add-on cards, the memory modules
are much higher capacity, and their is an incentive to take every extra cent
of cost out of a board (motherboards are very low margin products). The good
boards have the standard I/O built in for reasons of performance and EMI, so
less slots are needed.

For a high end file server there are still expensive full-size boards available,
usually EISA (yes it's alive and well for servers that need many network cards).

The other reason is that the motherboards MUST get smaller to keep trace lengths
shorter as speeds increase. The latest motherboards I saw with the Intel Triton
chip set are very small, have more layers, and some have components on both sides.
More layers with less area costs more than more area with less layers, but works 
better.

