Ken Snyder (kens@lsid.hp.com) wrote:
: As I look at the newer higher performance PCI bus motherboards I
: notice that many of them are switching more slots to PCI and away
: from ISA.  Many have gone to 4 PCI and 4 ISA.  I can only think of
: a couple of components that NEED PCI performance:  video and disc
: interfaces (and Maybe LAN).  My concern lies with the fact that I
: have 6 ISA devices (int. modem, scanner, I/O, sound card, video
: capture, IEEE-488) and even if the I/O is built into the disc
: controller or mb, I still need 5 ISA slots.  My current VLB mb
: has 3 VLB slots but allows them to also be used as ISA.  PCI seems
: not to allow this dual purpose scheme.  Will we soon be seeing
: PCI bus -modems? -sound cards?  In the real world of today,

: I need my, I need my, I need my ISA!

You need it, but you are not the normal user (no insult intended).

A modern motherboard has the I/O on board PCI-IDE, High speed
serial ports, ECP/EPP parallel port, floppy controller.

PCI slots are used for Ethernet and Video. For a file server you
may want several Ethernet cards and do bridging in the server to
keep the number of nodes per segment down (and performance up).

ISA slots are used for the sound card and fax/modem, though some
PCI motherboards now include both of these functions as well.

The scanner connects to an IEEE 1284 parallel port or you install
a PCI SCSI card.

So YOU can use ISA slots for IEEE 488, Modem, Sound, and Video Capture.
Use PCI for SCSI and Video and LAN. Use on-board serial/parallel/FDC/IDE.

You could go to an external modem, but the performance of an internal
modem is likely to be much better since a good internal modem runs the
parallel to serial conversion faster and with more buffering than a
16550 UART.




